<?xml version="1.0"?>
<!--
  ============================================================================
  Clickhouse small-host tuning (applied 2026-04-22)
  ============================================================================

  WHAT THIS FILE DOES:
    Overrides three classes of Clickhouse defaults so that our deployment on
    rishi-3 doesn't oversubscribe the 8 CPU cores with background merge work.

  WHY IT EXISTS:
    Upstream Clickhouse's defaults are "production-scale" — sized for a
    dedicated 32+ core / 64+ GB box running ONLY Clickhouse. On rishi-3 we:
      - Share 8 cores with ~30 other Sentry containers + etcd + Patroni.
      - Allocate 16 GB of RAM via docker-compose mem_limit (was 4 GB before).
      - Ingest a few events/sec of application traffic — TINY compared to
        the scale the defaults are sized for.

    The symptom that triggered this file: Beszel alerting sustained > 90 %
    CPU, load avg 20+ on an 8-core box. Root cause: 12 concurrent background
    merges (in a pool of 32 slots) saturating all cores. Merges themselves
    are cheap individually; it's the concurrency that broke us.

  HOW IT'S DELIVERED:
    docker-compose.override.yml in this repo mounts THIS DIRECTORY as
    read-only at /etc/clickhouse-server/config.d/ in the Clickhouse
    container. Clickhouse auto-loads every *.xml file in that directory at
    startup and merges them on top of the built-in defaults — the last
    value wins, per Clickhouse's XML merge rules.

  HOW TO ROLL BACK:
    Delete (or comment-out) the volume mount from docker-compose.override.yml
    and re-run scripts/install.sh. Clickhouse reverts to the built-in
    defaults on next start. No data loss.

  WHEN TO REVISIT:
    If sustained events/sec rate grows ~10× beyond today's level (~30
    events/sec or more), the 4-merge-slot cap could start creating
    part-accumulation pressure (TOO_MANY_PARTS warnings, then errors).
    At that point raise background_pool_size from 4 → 8 (or higher) and
    ratio from 1 → 2. See Clickhouse docs: background merges.
  ============================================================================
-->
<clickhouse>

  <!-- ====================================================================
       Background merge concurrency
       ====================================================================
       Default: background_pool_size=16, ratio=2 → 32 max merge tasks.
       Our override: 4 × 1 = 4 max merge tasks. 8× reduction.

       With Kafka → Sentry ingest running continuously, Clickhouse is
       constantly receiving small new parts that need merging into larger
       ones. Each merge reads N parts, combines + sorts, writes one part.
       That's read-heavy + CPU-heavy. At 32-concurrent on 8 cores it's 4x
       oversubscribed. At 4-concurrent we have room for the consumers,
       query serving, and other tenants on rishi-3 too. -->
  <background_pool_size>4</background_pool_size>
  <background_merges_mutations_concurrency_ratio>1</background_merges_mutations_concurrency_ratio>

  <!-- Companion pool sizes — keep them proportional. These rarely matter
       for us (no replication fetches, no ZooKeeper-heavy operations) but
       the defaults (16 each) are also oversized. -->
  <background_fetches_pool_size>2</background_fetches_pool_size>
  <background_common_pool_size>2</background_common_pool_size>

  <!-- ====================================================================
       Memory
       ====================================================================
       By default Clickhouse computes max_server_memory_usage as a fraction
       of either total host RAM or the cgroup mem_limit, depending on
       version. Before this change we observed MEMORY_LIMIT_EXCEEDED with
       "maximum: 1.20 GiB" despite a 4 GB container limit — Clickhouse was
       being conservative and only using ~30 % of its available memory.

       Pin to 0.9 (90 %) of container mem_limit. With docker-compose.override's
       new mem_limit=16g, Clickhouse will use up to ~14.4 GB — well beyond
       anything our current workload could demand but simple and safe. -->
  <max_server_memory_usage_to_ram_ratio>0.9</max_server_memory_usage_to_ram_ratio>

</clickhouse>
